<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-382-214  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 382 214.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Personal Computing  May 25 1990 v14 n5 p96(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fonts on the fly. (new DOS-compatible font technologies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Antonoff, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Font-scaling technology is moving into the MS-DOS laser printerworld and is becoming less expensive.andP;  The PostScript pagedescription language built into the original Apple LaserWriterprinter has long given Macintosh users the ability to use scalableoutline fonts, but the technology is costly.andP;  Non-PostScriptprinters that can scale fonts are now available.andP;  Bit-mapped fontsare stored as a fixed pattern of dots that cannot be changed andare limited to installed sizes.andP;  True font scaling eliminates theoverhead of storing bit maps on disk by creating fonts frommathematical outlines and storing the resulting bit map in printerRAM.andP;  HP's LaserJet III and Canon's LBP-4 laser printers includeresident scalable fonts; HP sells scalable soft fonts and fontcartridges.andP;  Some new software, such as Software Publishing Corp'sFirst Publisher 3.0, can create instant bit-mapped fonts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Desktop publishingFontsNew TechniqueSoftware DesignTrends.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>